knowledge/gold_standards/backward_facing_step.yaml:19:#   The comparator's 10% tolerance absorbs the 0.02 literature spread
knowledge/gold_standards/backward_facing_step.yaml:29:  reference_correlation_context: "The stored reference_values[].value=6.26 is a blended engineering anchor (see header block). Le/Moin/Kim 1997 DNS at Re_H=5100 reports 6.28; Driver & Seegmiller 1985 experiment at Re_H≈37500 reports 6.26; both bracket the post-transition plateau at our whitelist Re_H=7600 well inside the 10% tolerance band. The anchor is cited as Le/Moin/Kim because their DNS is the closer-regime literature; the 0.02 numerical offset vs the stored 6.26 is treated as within-tolerance rather than as a pure-DNS claim. No tight <2% sensitivity claim is made — the plateau is qualitative, and the residual drift depends on expansion ratio (1.2 DNS vs 1.125 adapter), inlet BL state, and the 2D-empty-patch simplification of the adapter path."
knowledge/gold_standards/backward_facing_step.yaml:31:    - condition: "Re_H sits in the post-transition regime where Xr/H is weakly Re-sensitive (7600 adapter vs 5100 reference, drift absorbed by 10% tolerance)"
knowledge/gold_standards/backward_facing_step.yaml:33:      evidence_ref: "src/foam_agent_adapter.py:1178-1184 — nu=1/Re=1/7600 with U_bulk=1. Regime argument documented in yaml header lines 6-13; accepted under Gate Q-4 Path A. The regime match is qualitative-plateau, not a 2% quantified tolerance."
knowledge/gold_standards/backward_facing_step.yaml:36:      evidence_ref: "src/foam_agent_adapter.py:1568 hardcoded `RASModel kEpsilon` in the BFS template (NOT kOmegaSST — earlier wording was wrong). div(phi,epsilon)/div(phi,k) schemes at ~1310 confirm RAS active. k-epsilon is the legacy BFS-benchmark RANS choice and is known to under-predict Xr/H slightly vs DNS; kOmegaSST or Reynolds-stress models track DNS better. RANS-vs-DNS is the standard literature compromise; Xr/H tolerance 0.10 absorbs the model-gap, but a RANS PASS is not a DNS PASS."
knowledge/gold_standards/backward_facing_step.yaml:42:      evidence_ref: "DEC-V61-052 Batch B: 1000-iter simpleFoam run under bounded-upwind + SIMPLEC + Spalding wall fn converges to Ux=2.66e-7, Uy=4.45e-7, p=1.26e-6, ε=2.48e-7, k=1.56e-7; continuity sum_local=7.31e-9, global=1.21e-9 (reports/phase5_fields/backward_facing_step/20260423T082933Z/log.simpleFoam). G3/G4/G5 gate battery all clean. Supersedes the pre-DEC-V61-052 ATTEST_HAZARD observation caused by the single-block generator diverging k/ε to 1e+30."
knowledge/gold_standards/backward_facing_step.yaml:43:  contract_status: "GEOMETRY_AND_GATES_GREEN_XR_UNDER_TOLERANCE — DEC-V61-052 closed the two defects V61-051 exposed (flat channel with no step; k/ε to 1e+30). The rewritten 3-block mesh produces a real BFS field (15154 pts, 0 points in step void, |U|_max=1.05·U_bulk) and the k-ε solver runs to full-length convergence with residuals in the 1e-7 range on 7360 cells. However, measured Xr/H ≈ 3.95 sits ~37% below the Driver 1985 reference of 6.26, outside the 10% tolerance band. This is within the known k-ε under-prediction envelope for BFS but on the high-magnitude side of it. Batch C (Codex review) will probe whether the gap is schemes/BCs (fixable) or the RANS-vs-DNS structural limit (accept + document). DEC-V61-052 lands the geometry+divergence fix; the Xr gate remains open."
